maml:description.maml:para: Get an authentication cookie from your IPA server in order to be able to use APIs

Get a valid authentication cookie from your IPA server based on login/password authentication. The websession is saved to a global variable in order to be reused for API authentication. You can import your credential from an encryoted file previously generated with Set-FreeIPAAPICrendentials and Set-FreeIPAAPIServerConfig cmdlets.

maml:Description.maml:para: URL of your FreeIPA server. https://myfreeipa.tld
use this setting to close the remote session with your FreeIPA server
use this setting to import URL and credential from global variables $FreeIPAAPICredentials and $FreeIPAAPIServerConfig
use this setting to close the remote session with your FreeIPA server
URL of your FreeIPA server. https://myfreeipa.tld
use this setting to import URL and credential from global variables $FreeIPAAPICredentials and $FreeIPAAPIServerConfig

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\> Get-FreeIPAAPIAuthenticationCookie -UseCachedURLandCredentials

dev:remarks.maml:para: Connect to your FreeIPA server based on config / credential set with Set-FreeIPAAPICrendentials cmdlet

maml:description.maml:para: Import from external config file, your previously saved credential to a global variable
Import your protected/ecrypted credential from %appdata%\Manage-FreeIPA\Manage-FreeIPA.xml (saved with Set-FreeIPAAPICredentials cmdlet) into $FreeIPAAPICredentials global variable.

maml:Description.maml:para: Master passowrd previously used to protect your external file.
Master passowrd previously used to protect your external file.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\> Import-FreeIPAAPICrendentials -MasterPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString -String "keypass" -AsPlainText -Force)

dev:remarks.maml:para: Import your encrypted credential protected by keypass passphrase into $FreeIPAAPICredential

maml:description.maml:para: Set your FreeIPA Credential in cache (powershell global variable) or external file backup (encrypted)

Set your FreeIPA Credential in cache (powershell global variable) or external file backup (encrypted) To import your backed up credential use Import-FreeIPAAPICredentials cmdlet. File hosted in %appdata%\Manage-FreeIPA\Manage-FreeIPA.xml

maml:Description.maml:para: Master passowrd to protect your external file.
Use this setting to remove the content of the current global variable.
Use this setting to export the credential in an external encrypted (password protected) file on local hard drive (%appdata%\Manage-FreeIPA\Manage-FreeIPA.xml)
Use this setting to remove the content of the current global variable.
Use this setting to export the credential in an external encrypted (password protected) file on local hard drive (%appdata%\Manage-FreeIPA\Manage-FreeIPA.xml)
Master passowrd to protect your external file.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\Set-FreeIPAAPICredentials -AdminLogin (ConvertTo-SecureString -String "adminlogin" -AsPlainText -Force) -AdminPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString -String "adminpass" -AsPlainText -Force) -MasterPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString -String "keypass" -AsPlainText -Force) -EncryptKeyInLocalFile

dev:remarks.maml:para: Encrypt (password protected passphrase : keypass in example) and set your credentials (adminlogin/adminpass in example) as global variable and export it into a config file on local hard drive.

maml:description.maml:para: Set your FreeIPA server URL and client version supported

Set your FreeIPA server URL and Client version supported. If client version is not set, version 2.229 is set by default. Warning : the CA (Certification authority) used by your FreeIPA server must be trusted on your system first.

maml:Description.maml:para: Set your FreeIPA server URL : https://youripaserver.domain.tld
Set your client version for API usage. Version 2.229 is set by default
Set your client version for API usage. Version 2.229 is set by default
Set your FreeIPA server URL : https://youripaserver.domain.tld

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\> Set-FreeIPAAPIServerConfig -URL https://youripaserver.domain.tld

dev:remarks.maml:para: Set your FreeIPA server to youripaserver.domain.tld
